title: For Sale:  August Wolf Combinatioin gun
postcontent: August Wolf Combination gun with two bbl sets. Both bbl sets are dated May 1939, and are serialized to the receiver. One bbl set is 16ga over 16ga measuring 28" long, and the other is 16ga 0ver 8mm Mauser measuring 25.5" long. This gun has been used and hunted with, and shows signs of use. Recoil pad has been replaced many years ago, which leads me to think the finish has at least been added to, if not refinished at some point in it's life. Finish is thinning is spots. Photos do not correctly show color of bluing - it is much darker in reality, but is also thinning some in spots, and shows light freckling in places. Not rust, but dark spots..... Case hardening colors have also faded to the point they are all but gone, except in hidden areas. Stock also has a few small dings, but no cracks or breaks. Somewhere in time the scope also took a hard left and disappeared. On the up side, bores are perfect, action locks up like a tank, and this gun should offer many more decades of use. Photos will show that the shotgun chambers are 2 3/4" - that is incorrect. they are chambered for 2 1/2" shells but someone measured the chamber and determined it was 2 3/4" long, but that is the distance to the begining of the forcing cone. Markings were applied here as the Germans would have marked it in millimeters. Do NOT fire 2 3/4" shells in this gun or pressures will rise significantly. I will stick a couple photos in the listing, but I can give you a link to a photobucket folder with many photos. Not able to poste a link here.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Femaru P. Mod 37, jhv43 rig with holster
location: Fort Thomas, Kentucky near Cincinnati, Northern Kentucky, Kentucky
postcontent: Will ship to an FFL or C&R with usual procedures for $20 from my C&R.  Well used but mechanically solid Femaru jhv43, P. Mod. 37, Nazi marked, .32 or 7.65 cal pistol.  All matching serial numbers, except magazine. The German's placed two orders (jhv 41 & jhv 43, in 1941 & 1943 respectively) with what is now FEG.  They used the basic design of the 37M 9 mm short, or .380 cal, Hungarian Military sidearm but in 7.65 mm cal., and had the factory incorporate a thumb safety.  A large number of these went to the Luftwaffe and other services where confined spaces warranted having a gun smaller than the P.38.  Well made and well designed.  This is a well used example that I have detailed stripped, cleaned, and tested fired.  Bore is quite good, finish splotchy as you see, but largely free of pitting, etc.  Shoulder holster is probably theater made, I don't have any history on it, but it appears to be about as old as the pistol.

Why forward-ejecting? Because it allows the RFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 Nato Bullpup ever developed. Upon firing, the patented, dual-extractor system pulls the fired case from the chamber and lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, where they. The Bullpup configuration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only 26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than its competitors with equal barrel lengths. Furthermore, the stock and mechanism cross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast to existing Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also one of the safest Bullpup ever developed becasue the breech is separated from the shooters face by two layers of 1.6mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansion is directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shooters head and face. The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automatic rifle in 7.62mm Nato caliber. It accepts standard metric FAL type magazines which work "drop free" and do not need to be tilted in. One 20 round magazine is included. Barrels on current models are 18" long; a longer barrel length of 24" available as the hunter variant. The muzzle is threaded 5/8x24 TPI and comes equipped with their A2-style flash hider. All controls are fully ambidextrous; the reciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The safety disconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. A Mil-Spec Picatinny rail is attached rigidly to the barrel assembly. No open sights are provided, allowing the user to select from optics and sight systems available on the market. The RFB comes with a two point sling that can be easily configured to suit the user's preference. Available accessories include a free-floating, four-sided Picatinny forend, bipod mounts, a removable bayonet lug for use with Nato style bayonets including their own Folding Bayonet, and many more.
